By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\begin{align*}
a^2 &= b^2 + b^2 - 2 \cdot b \cdot b \cdot \cos A \\
&= 2b^2 - 2b^2 \cos A.
\end{align*}

Hence,
\[2b^2 - 2b^2 \cos A = 128 - 128 \cos \frac{A}{2}.\]Let $x = \cos \frac{A}{2},$ so $0 < x < 1.$  Then $2 - 2x^2 = 16 - 16x,$ or $x^2 - 8x + 7 = 0.$  This factors as $(x - 1)(x - 7) = 0,$ so $x = 1$ or $x = 7.$

If $x = 1,$ then $\frac{A}{2} = 0,$ so $A = 0^\circ,$ contradiction.  Hence, $x = 7,$ so $\cos A = 2x^2 - 1 = 95,$ which is negative.  Thus, there are no solutions in positive integers.

